{
  "texts": [
    "In the form presented by Sutton and Barto (2018) in Eq. 7, the state-value function v π (s) demonstrates the notions of probability and transition, making the relationship explicit between the value of a state and the values of its successor states.",
    "In turn, the action-value functions q π (s, a) seek to estimate the total expected reward if the agent takes an action a in the state s and follows the policy π, allowing it to assess the utility of each possible action at that state (Eq. 8).",
    "In MDPs, a policy π is better or equivalent to another policy π if v π (s) ≥ v π (s), ∀s ∈ S. In all cases, at least one optimal policy π * is better than or equal to all others.",
    "These poli- cies share the same optimal state-value function v * (s) = max π v π (s), which is the high- 1 3 est value that can be obtained for each state, and the same optimal action-value function q * (s, a) = max π q π (s, a), ∀s, a ∈ S, A (Sutton and Barto 2018).",
    "It is possible to write the optimal action-value function relative to the optimal state-value function so that q * (s, a) = E[R t+1 + γv * (S t+1) | S t = s, A t = a]."
  ]
}